I am coding a custom Android soft keyboard app. In the settings page of the app, there is a SeekBar that resizes the height of the keyboard.

I am encountering a bug where, when the keyboard is downsized using the SeekBar, the keys shrink as expected but the keyboard does not drop down to the bottom of the screen. Only if the SeekBar is touched again does the keyboard get repositioned at the bottom of the screen.

(There is no bug when the keyboard grows in size.)

In the input method service's `onStartInputView`, I have the following:

```java
  @Override
  public void onStartInputView(final EditorInfo editorInfo, final boolean isRestarting)
  {
    super.onStartInputView(editorInfo, isRestarting);

    for (final Keyboard keyboard : keyboardSet)
    {
      keyboard.adjustKeyboardHeight();
    }
    inputContainer.updateHeight();
    // etc.
  }
```

`keyboard.adjustKeyboardHeight()` applies a multiplier to the y-directional variables of each key.

`inputContainer.updateHeight()` calls `requestLayout()`on the keyboard view, which holds the keyboard and its keys.

`inputContainer` is a FrameLayout containing the keyboard view (among other things).

1. Why isn't the `requestLayout` call sufficient to reposition the keyboard?
2. How do I programmatically force the keyboard to be repositioned at the bottom of the screen on the *first* use of the SeekBar? (Calculating the height difference is not an option; there is surely a way to trigger the repositioning automatically.)

1. The `requestLayout()` call updates the layout of the view hierarchy, but it does not force the keyboard view to move to the bottom of the screen. It simply recalculates the size and position of the keyboard view within its parent container. To move the view to the bottom of the screen, you will need to update its position in code.

2. To programmatically force the keyboard to be repositioned at the bottom of the screen on the first use of the SeekBar, you can add a listener to the SeekBar that checks if the keyboard view is currently at the bottom of the screen. If it is not, you can update the position of the keyboard view using the `layout()` method. For example:

```java
seekBar.setOnSeekBarChangeListener(new SeekBar.OnSeekBarChangeListener() {
  @Override
  public void onProgressChanged(SeekBar seekBar, int progress, boolean fromUser) {
    // update the size of the keyboard
    keyboard.adjustKeyboardHeight();
    inputContainer.updateHeight();

    // check if the keyboard is at the bottom of the screen
    if (inputContainer.getHeight() + inputContainer.getTop() != screenHeight) {
      // if not, move the keyboard to the bottom of the screen
      int keyboardHeight = inputContainer.getHeight();
      inputContainer.layout(0, screenHeight - keyboardHeight, screenWidth, screenHeight);
    }
  }
  // ...
});
```

This code calculates the current height and top position of the keyboard view using its container's `getHeight()` and `getTop()` methods. If the sum of those values does not equal the height of the screen, it means the keyboard is not at the bottom of the screen, so the `layout()` method is called to move the keyboard to the bottom of the screen. The `screenWidth` and `screenHeight` variables should be set to the width and height of the screen in pixels.

The behavior you describe suggests that the layout of the keyboard is being updated correctly when the SeekBar is interacted with for the first time, but the keyboard is not being positioned correctly until the SeekBar is interacted with a second time.

This could indicate that the positioning code you are using (`layout()` method) is being called before the keyboard layout has been fully calculated and updated. When the SeekBar is interacted with a second time, the layout has already been updated, so the positioning occurs correctly.

To solve this issue, you can delay the positioning code until the keyboard layout has been fully updated. One way to do this is to post a runnable to the keyboard view's message queue using the `post()` method. This ensures that the runnable is executed after the layout has been fully calculated.

Here's how you can modify the code from my previous answer to use `post()`:

```java
seekBar.setOnSeekBarChangeListener(new SeekBar.OnSeekBarChangeListener() {
  @Override
  public void onProgressChanged(SeekBar seekBar, int progress, boolean fromUser) {
    // update the size of the keyboard
    keyboard.adjustKeyboardHeight();
    inputContainer.updateHeight();

    // check if the keyboard is at the bottom of the screen
    if (inputContainer.getHeight() + inputContainer.getTop() != screenHeight) {
      // post a runnable to move the keyboard to the bottom of the screen
      inputContainer.post(new Runnable() {
        @Override
        public void run() {
          int keyboardHeight = inputContainer.getHeight();
          inputContainer.layout(0, screenHeight - keyboardHeight, screenWidth, screenHeight);
        }
      });
    }
  }
  // ...
});
```

This code creates a new runnable that moves the keyboard to the bottom of the screen, and posts it to the message queue using `inputContainer.post()`. The `run()` method of the runnable will be executed after the layout has been fully updated, ensuring that the keyboard is positioned correctly.

To post a `Runnable` for an object being drawn, you can use the `post(Runnable)` method on the view that includes the object being drawn. 

For example, if you have a custom `View` that includes a drawable object that you need to update, you can use `post(Runnable)` to update the drawable object after the view's layout has been fully updated:

```java
public class MyCustomView extends View {
    private MyDrawable mDrawable;

    // ...

    @Override
    protected void onSizeChanged(int w, int h, int oldw, int oldh) {
        super.onSizeChanged(w, h, oldw, oldh);

        // create a new instance of MyDrawable and set its size
        mDrawable = new MyDrawable();
        mDrawable.setBounds(0, 0, w, h);

        // post a runnable to update the drawable object
        post(new Runnable() {
            @Override
            public void run() {
                mDrawable.update();
                invalidate();
            }
        });
    }

    @Override
    protected void onDraw(Canvas canvas) {
        super.onDraw(canvas);

        // draw the drawable object on the canvas
        mDrawable.draw(canvas);
    }

    // ...
}
```

In this example, when `onSizeChanged()` is called, a new instance of `MyDrawable` is created and its bounds are set to match the size of the view. Then, a runnable is created and posted using the `post(Runnable)` method. The runnable updates the `MyDrawable` object and invalidates the view, triggering a redraw. 

The drawable object is then drawn in the `onDraw()` method by calling its `draw()` method on the `Canvas` object passed to `onDraw()`.

If you try to cast a `View`'s `getParent()` result to a `LinearLayout` and it is not an instance of `LinearLayout`, a `ClassCastException` will be thrown.

The `ClassCastException` is a runtime exception that can occur when you try to cast an object to a type that is not compatible with its actual type. It extends the `RuntimeException` class, which means that it is an unchecked exception and does not need to be handled by a `catch` block (although it can be caught and handled if desired). 

Here's an example of how a `ClassCastException` might be caught when trying to cast a `View`'s `getParent()` result to `LinearLayout`:

```java
View myView = findViewById(R.id.my_view);
ViewGroup parent = (ViewGroup) myView.getParent();
if (parent instanceof LinearLayout) {
  LinearLayout linearLayout = (LinearLayout) parent;
  // do something with linearLayout
} else {
  // handle case where parent is not a LinearLayout
  Log.e(TAG, "Parent is not a LinearLayout");
}
```

In this example, the `getParent()` result is first cast to a `ViewGroup`, which is the parent class of all view groups. Then, an `instanceof` check is used to determine if the parent is a `LinearLayout`. If it is, the cast to `LinearLayout` is performed and the `linearLayout` variable can be used. If it is not, an error message is logged.

Catching the `ClassCastException` certainly provides a simpler alternative to checking the `instanceof` the parent and handling the case where it is not a `LinearLayout`. It allows you to write more concise code, since you only need to cast the parent to `LinearLayout` and handle the resulting exception if it occurs.

Here's an example of how you could use a `try`-`catch` block to cast the `getParent()` result to `LinearLayout` and handle the `ClassCastException`:

```java
View myView = findViewById(R.id.my_view);
try {
    LinearLayout linearLayout = (LinearLayout) myView.getParent();
    // do something with linearLayout
} catch (ClassCastException e) {
    // handle case where parent is not a LinearLayout
    Log.e(TAG, "Parent is not a LinearLayout", e);
}
```

This code tries to cast the `getParent()` result directly to `LinearLayout`. If the parent is not an instance of `LinearLayout`, a `ClassCastException` is thrown and caught in the `catch` block. In the `catch` block, you can handle the case where the parent is not a `LinearLayout`. 

Note that catching the exception can result in more concise code, but it can also make it harder to debug since it can hide issues that result in runtime exceptions. It's generally recommended to use exceptions sparingly and only handle those that are likely to occur and for which you have a clear plan for how to handle them.

To post a `Runnable` that calls `requestLayout()` on `inputContainer` the next time it is drawn, you can use the `postOnAnimation(Runnable)` method on `inputContainer`. This method posts the `Runnable` to the message queue that will be executed after the current frame is drawn.

Here's an example of how to use `postOnAnimation(Runnable)` to request a layout on `inputContainer` the next time it is drawn:

```java
final Runnable postRequestLayout = new Runnable() {
  @Override
  public void run() {
    inputContainer.requestLayout();
  }
};

// post the request on the message queue
inputContainer.postOnAnimation(postRequestLayout);
```

In this example, a `Runnable` called `postRequestLayout` is defined that calls `inputContainer.requestLayout()` when executed. This `Runnable` is then posted to the message queue using `postOnAnimation(Runnable)`.

Alternatively, you can use the `ViewTreeObserver.OnPreDrawListener` interface to listen for the next draw pass and run a `Runnable` before the view is drawn. Here's an example:

```java
// create an OnPreDrawListener instance
ViewTreeObserver.OnPreDrawListener preDrawListener = new ViewTreeObserver.OnPreDrawListener() {
  @Override
  public boolean onPreDraw() {
    inputContainer.getViewTreeObserver().removeOnPreDrawListener(this);
    inputContainer.requestLayout();
    return true;
  }
};

// add the OnPreDrawListener to the view tree observer
inputContainer.getViewTreeObserver().addOnPreDrawListener(preDrawListener);
```

This code creates an instance of `ViewTreeObserver.OnPreDrawListener` and implements its `onPreDraw()` method, which is called before the view is drawn. In `onPreDraw()`, the `preDrawListener` instance removes itself from the view tree observer and calls `inputContainer.requestLayout()`. Then it returns `true` to indicate that the draw should proceed. Finally, `preDrawListener` is added to the view tree observer using `addOnPreDrawListener()`. 

Using `ViewTreeObserver.OnPreDrawListener` allows you to run a `Runnable` before the view is drawn, while still being able to get called before the view is drawn, without having to delay your request.
